---
// src/pages/faq.astro
import Page from '../layouts/Page.astro';
import BuyButton from '../components/BuyButton.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [{ name: 'FAQ', href: '/faq/' }];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Do I need any botanical knowledge to use these guides?',
    a: `No. You don't need experience or botanical knowledge. The method is designed around
        what you can see and touch in the field — bark texture along with fruit, bud, and
        leaf traits. You learn to ask: does the bark peel in long ribbons? Grip in hard
        furrows? Shed cleanly to smooth white? Where botanical terms do appear they're
        explained in context or in the concise glossary. Some species can still be tricky
        — even eucalypt gurus will testify to that — but you don't need a science background
        to get started, have fun, and successfully identify trees.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Does the guide cover my suburb?',
    a: `The Melbourne edition covers the greater Melbourne region — broadly from the Dandenong
        Ranges in the east toward the Otway foothills, including many of Melbourne's parks
        and bushland reserves.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Does it include a species key?',
    a: `Yes — there's a visual key that groups species by stable field traits. Once you've placed a tree in a bark category,
        you're looking at a manageable shortlist of candidates. The fruit narrows it further, though some species can still
        be close calls and that's part of the beauty of eucalypts!`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Do I need to wait for the tree to flower?',
    a: `No. The method used in the book makes use of the various traits of a tree — bark, fruit, buds, adult and juvenile leaves —
        giving you many pieces of the eucalypt puzzle.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Does it include indigenous knowledge?',
    a: `This book includes some of this information but it is just one entry point to the vastness of Indigenous knowledge
        connected to eucalypts. The guide recognises that these trees have been known, named, and utilised for tens of thousands
        of years, and the First Nations people connected to their country through intimate knowledge and care of Country.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'I\'ve never been able to identify a tree. Will this actually work for me?',
    a: `It's a great starting point for beginners as well as those with some experience. It has been tried and tested in the field,
        and it works! The method is step-by-step and the photography is detailed and diagnostic. Many people find they can make
        a plausible identification fairly quickly. Some species are more straightforward than others, and there may be individual
        trees you can't pin down — even the keenest 'experts' are often perplexed by these wonderful species.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Will I actually learn to identify eucalypts, or will I just be looking things up each time?',
    a: `This will depend on your level of engagement — like learning any group of plants,
        the more time you spend observing them in the field, the more confident you become.
        The guide is built around a repeatable method rather than a list of facts. This
        helps you build real understanding of each species. Many users find they gradually
        recognise key features without needing to check every detail. At the same time,
        it also works as a reference. Even experienced botanists return to guides like
        this to confirm identifications.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Do I need to know botanical language?',
    a: `No. The Guide uses plain English so it can be used by everyone. It's designed to
        avoid the frustration of constantly flipping back and forth to decode technical
        language. Where specialist terms are included, they are explained nearby so you
        can keep reading without interruption.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'What does each species entry include?',
    a: `Each species page includes detailed, life-sized photographs of buds, fruit, and
        leaves — showing both juvenile and adult foliage, which can often look quite different.

        Bark is also shown for each species, along with variation within certain species.
        Identification notes highlight the key features that distinguish similar or easily
        confused species.

        Distribution maps and basic habitat information are also included to help place
        each species in context.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Will I learn about the local ecology — not just the names?',
    a: `The guide includes context on geology, ecology, eucalypt evolution, and the role
        these trees play in supporting local fauna.

        As a field guide, it's designed to deliver this information in a practical,
        accessible form while you're out observing trees in their natural environment.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Is it actually pocket-sized?',
    a: `It's a compact softcover guide — under 60 pages — designed to be taken into the
        field with you. Whether it fits in a pocket will depend on the size of the pocket,
        but it is light, portable, and easy to carry.

        The photographs are life-sized to allow for straightforward comparison with trees
        in the field.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I use it with children or in an educational setting?',
    a: `The visual, step-by-step method works well for younger learners, and the
        bark-first approach can be engaging for kids. The Indigenous knowledge and other
        supporting information is also valued in educational contexts.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Is it just for botanists and serious naturalists?',
    a: `Not at all — it's written for anyone curious about the trees around them.
        Bushwalkers, gardeners, people who pass the same trees every day and want to
        know what they're looking at. Botanists may find it a useful quick reference too.
        It is accessible without being superficial.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I buy a copy?',
    a: `The guide is available directly through this website via secure Stripe checkout —
        $30 AUD per copy plus $7.50 postage &amp; handling anywhere in Australia. No account needed.
        You can also order through any Australian bookshop using the ISBN.
        Bulk and wholesale orders: email info@eucalyptsmelbourne.au.`,
  },
];

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: faqs.map(({ q, a }) => ({
    '@type': 'Question',
    name: q,
    acceptedAnswer: {
      '@type': 'Answer',
      text: a.replace(/\s+/g, ' ').trim(),
    },
  })),
};
---

<Page
  title="FAQ — ACE Guide to Eucalypts"
  description="Frequently asked questions about the ACE Guide to Eucalypts Melbourne. Do you need botanical knowledge? Does it cover your suburb? Does it include indigenous knowledge?"
  schemaJson={faqSchema}
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <h1>Frequently asked questions</h1>

  <p class="faq-intro">
    Everything you want to know before picking up the guide — and a few things
    you didn't know you wanted to know.
  </p>

  <div class="faq-list">
    {faqs.map(({ q, a }) => (
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-question">{q}</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          {a.trim().split(/\n\s*\n/).map(para => (
            <p set:html={para.trim().replace(/\n/g, ' ')} />
          ))}
        </div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="faq-cta">
    <p>Ready to take one into the bush?</p>
    <div class="faq-buttons">
      <BuyButton text="Buy Melbourne — $30 AUD" href="https://buy.stripe.com/00w3cn2Wi7Yq7uf3pXgjC01" external={true} />
    </div>
    <p class="faq-secure">Secure checkout via Stripe. No account needed.</p>
  </div>
</Page>

<style>
  .faq-intro {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .faq-list {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
  }

  .faq-item {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-olive);
  }

  .faq-item:last-of-type {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-olive);
  }

  .faq-question {
    display: block;
    padding: var(--space-md) 0;
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    position: relative;
    padding-right: 2rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
  }

  .faq-question::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .faq-question::after {
    content: '+';
    position: absolute;
    right: 0;
    top: var(--space-md);
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    font-weight: 300;
    color: var(--color-olive);
    line-height: 1;
    transition: transform 150ms ease;
  }

  details[open] .faq-question::after {
    content: '−';
  }

  .faq-question:hover {
    color: var(--color-cta);
  }

  .faq-answer {
    padding-bottom: var(--space-md);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .faq-answer p + p {
    margin-top: var(--space-sm);
  }

  /* CTA */
  .faq-cta {
    margin-top: var(--space-xl);
    padding-top: var(--space-lg);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .faq-cta > p:first-child {
    font-family: var(--font-heading);
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .faq-buttons {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-sm);
    justify-content: center;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .faq-secure {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
  }
</style>
